ngs, weekly church attendance among evangelicals is substantially higher than the national average, church attendees say they get significant enjoyment from their religious groups, youth participation is high, and evangelicals are more likely to volunteer. While there may be signs of decline on the horizon, Canadian evangelical congregations seem to remain vital at a time when most other Christian traditions are waning. A clearly presented study of evangelical beliefs, organizations, leaders, and finances, A Culture of Faith reveals the current strength of evangelical Protestantism and its implications for the future of religion in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian sociologyzCanada. 0aChurch attendancezCanada. 0aEvangelicalismzCanada. 0aReligious gatheringsxChristianity. 0aReligious gatheringszCanada. 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Evangelism.2bisacsh1 aHiemstra, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenner, Jamesr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilkinson, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359713640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597136/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles